<h2>How to Use Free Detectors Effectively</h2>
<h3>Do Not Trust a Single Tool</h3>
<p>Run text through multiple detectors. If three tools agree, the signal is stronger. If they disagree, treat the result as inconclusive.</p>
<h3>Use Them as Signals, Not Verdicts</h3>
<p>A detector flagging text as 70% AI is not proof. It is a signal that the text might need closer review. Always use human judgment.</p>
<h3>Test on Your Own Writing</h3>
<p>Run your own human-written text through detectors to see your baseline. If you consistently trigger false positives, you know the tool is unreliable for your writing style.</p>
<h3>Be Aware of the Limitations</h3>
<p>Free detectors are generally less accurate than paid versions. They often:</p>
<ul>
<li>Miss edited or paraphrased AI text</li>
<li>Flag formal human writing as AI</li>
<li>Struggle with newer AI models</li>
<li>Fail on non-English text</li>
</ul>
<h2>When Free Detectors Are Not Enough</h2>
<p>Free tools work for casual checks. They are insufficient for:</p>
<ul>
<li>Academic integrity decisions</li>
<li>Publisher submission screening</li>
<li>Legal or compliance requirements</li>
<li>High-volume content workflows</li>
</ul>
<p>In these cases, paid tools with human review processes are more appropriate — though still not perfect.</p>
